<p><sup><a name="fn135" href="#fnB135">[134]</a></sup> 	See Wilcox, above n 4,
92&#8211;3:</p>
<p>Where the court is not satisfied that the claimants' circumstances are
sufficiently related, it has no power to allow the action to
continue as a
representative proceeding ... The advantage of representative proceedings is
that issues common to all the claimants
can be determined at one hearing ... But
an absence of 'relatedness' undermines the rationale of the proceeding; any
hearing would
necessarily degenerate into a jumbled trial of disparate
actions.</p>
